Reversal is the single most important primitive in this module — you will write this exact loop inside a dozen different problems. Three pointers walk the list together: `prev` trails, `cur` leads, and `nxt` keeps a grip on the rest of the list *before* you clobber `cur->next`.

```cpp
struct ListNode {
    int val;
    ListNode* next;
    ListNode(int x) : val(x), next(nullptr) {}
};

// ---- In-place reversal (the single most important primitive) ----
// Walk the list, flipping each node's next pointer to point backwards.
// prev trails, cur leads, nxt saves the rest before we clobber cur->next.
ListNode* reverse(ListNode* head) {
    ListNode* prev = nullptr;
    ListNode* cur  = head;
    while (cur) {
        ListNode* nxt = cur->next; // 1. stash the rest of the list
        cur->next = prev;          // 2. reverse this link
        prev = cur;                // 3. advance prev
        cur = nxt;                 // 4. advance cur
    }
    return prev; // prev is the new head (old tail)
}
```

Memorize it as a four-beat chant: **save, flip, walk prev, walk cur.**

[[fig:m05-reverse-step]]

> [!EXAMPLE]
> Trace on `1→2→3`:
> - start: `prev = ∅`, `cur = 1`
> - iter 1: save `nxt=2`, flip `1→∅`; now `prev=1, cur=2`
> - iter 2: save `nxt=3`, flip `2→1`; now `prev=2, cur=3`
> - iter 3: save `nxt=∅`, flip `3→2`; now `prev=3, cur=∅` — loop ends
> - return `prev` → node 3, and the list reads `3→2→1`.

> [!PITFALL]
> The #1 reversal bug: writing `cur->next = prev` **before** stashing `cur->next` into `nxt`. The instant you flip the link, the unvisited suffix becomes unreachable. If your reversed list mysteriously contains one node, this is why — save first, flip second.

Half of all list bugs come from one special case: *the head itself might change*. Delete the first node, merge two lists, reverse the first block of k — suddenly `head` is not the head anymore, and your code sprouts `if (cur == head)` branches everywhere.

The fix costs one line: allocate a fake node **in front of** the list. Now every real node — including the old head — has a node before it, so the exact same unlink move works everywhere. At the end you return `dummy.next`, which is the true head no matter what surgery happened.

```cpp
// ---- Dummy-node skeleton (deletion / merging / building output) ----
ListNode* templateWithDummy(ListNode* head) {
    ListNode dummy(0);        // fake node BEFORE the head
    dummy.next = head;
    ListNode* prev = &dummy;  // prev always points at the node before "cur"
    ListNode* cur  = head;
    while (cur) {
        // ... decide to keep or unlink cur ...
        // to delete cur:  prev->next = cur->next; cur = cur->next;
        // to keep   cur:  prev = cur;             cur = cur->next;
    }
    return dummy.next;        // head may have changed — this is why we used dummy
}
```

[[fig:m05-dummy-delete]]

> [!KEY]
> Ask one question before coding: **can the first node be deleted, moved, or replaced?** If yes — dummy node, no exceptions. If the head is guaranteed to survive (find the middle, detect a cycle), you can skip it.

> [!EXAM]
> When you *build* an output list (merge, add-two-numbers), start from a stack-allocated `ListNode dummy(0)` and append via a `tail` pointer. The empty-output edge case then handles itself: `dummy.next` is simply `nullptr`. No `if (!result)` gymnastics under time pressure.

One pointer takes two steps for every single step of the other. This tiny trick answers questions that *look* like they need the length of the list — without ever counting:

- **Middle:** when `fast` runs out of road, `slow` has covered exactly half the distance — it is standing on the middle node.
- **Cycle:** if the list loops, `fast` enters the cycle and starts lapping `slow`. The gap between them shrinks by exactly one node per step, so they *must* collide — no jumping over. (Finding the cycle's *entry* is Deep Dive 1.)
- **k-th from the end:** a cousin — give the front pointer a head start of `k` steps, then move both at the same speed; when the front one hits the end, the back one is `k` from the end.

```cpp
// ---- Fast/slow: find middle (slow lands on 2nd middle for even length) ----
ListNode* middle(ListNode* head) {
    ListNode* slow = head;
    ListNode* fast = head;
    while (fast && fast->next) {
        slow = slow->next;
        fast = fast->next->next;
    }
    return slow;
}
```

[[fig:m05-fastslow-middle]]

> [!PITFALL]
> The guard must be `while (fast && fast->next)` — **check `fast` first**. Short-circuit evaluation bails out before `fast->next` dereferences null. On even-length lists `fast` genuinely becomes `nullptr` mid-flight, so `while (fast->next)` alone is a guaranteed crash.

Even-length lists have *two* middles, and your guard decides which one `slow` lands on:

| guard | slow ends on (even length) |
|---|---|
| `while (fast && fast->next)` | the **second** middle |
| `while (fast->next && fast->next->next)` | the node **before** the split |

Pick deliberately: splitting a list in half (Reorder List, merge sort on lists) wants the *before-the-split* version; a plain **return the middle node** wants the first.

deepdives.answer:
**Why naive fails.** A hash set of visited nodes finds the cycle in $O(n)$ time — but $O(n)$ space. The interview twist is always *$O(1)$ space*, which kills the set outright.

**Phase 1 — detection.** Move `slow` by 1 and `fast` by 2. No cycle → `fast` falls off the end. Cycle → `fast` enters the loop and closes in on `slow` from behind: the gap shrinks by exactly 1 node per step, so a collision is *guaranteed* — it cannot jump over.

**Phase 2 — the genuinely clever part.** Let `a` = distance from head to the cycle entry, `b` = distance from the entry to the meeting point, `c` = cycle length.

[[fig:m05-floyd-entry]]

At the moment of collision:

- slow travelled $a + b$
- fast travelled $a + b + k \cdot c$ for some $k \ge 1$ (it lapped the cycle $k$ times)
- fast went exactly twice as far: $2(a+b) = a+b+k\cdot c \implies a+b = k\cdot c \implies a = k\cdot c - b$

> [!KEY]
> $k\cdot c - b$ is precisely the *forward* walking distance from the meeting point back around to the entry. So the head is `a` steps from the entry — and the meeting point is **also** effectively `a` steps from the entry. **Reset one pointer to head, advance both one step at a time, and they collide exactly at the entry.** No arithmetic at runtime; the equation is baked into the walk.

```cpp
ListNode* detectCycle(ListNode* head) {
    ListNode *slow = head, *fast = head;
    while (fast && fast->next) {
        slow = slow->next;
        fast = fast->next->next;
        if (slow == fast) {              // collision => cycle exists
            ListNode* p = head;
            while (p != slow) {          // a == k*c - b, so they meet at entry
                p = p->next;
                slow = slow->next;
            }
            return p;                    // the cycle's entry node
        }
    }
    return nullptr;                      // fast hit the end => no cycle
}
```

**Complexity:** $O(n)$ time, $O(1)$ space.

**What generalizes:** the $a = k\cdot c - b$ derivation *is* the interview — be ready to reproduce it on a whiteboard. The same collision argument powers **Find the Duplicate Number** (treat the array as a linked list via `i → nums[i]`) and loop detection in iterated functions.

**Why naive fails.** You cannot walk backwards in a singly-linked list, so *grab the last node* costs $O(n)$ every time → $O(n^2)$ total. Copying node pointers into a vector works in $O(n)$ time but spends $O(n)$ space — the elegant answer needs none.

> [!INTUITION]
> The target order interleaves the first half (forward) with the second half (*backward*). You cannot walk backward — but you can **make** the second half walk forward by reversing it. The problem dissolves into three primitives you already own.

**The decomposition:**

1. **Find the middle** with fast/slow (the *before-the-split* variant).
2. **Reverse the second half** — your memorized four-beat loop.
3. **Weave the two halves alternately**, taking one node from each.

```cpp
void reorderList(ListNode* head) {
    if (!head || !head->next) return;
    // 1. middle: slow ends at the start of the second half
    ListNode *slow = head, *fast = head;
    while (fast->next && fast->next->next) { slow = slow->next; fast = fast->next->next; }
    // 2. reverse the second half
    ListNode *second = slow->next; slow->next = nullptr; // split
    ListNode *prev = nullptr;
    while (second) { ListNode* n = second->next; second->next = prev; prev = second; second = n; }
    second = prev;                        // head of reversed second half
    // 3. weave the two lists together
    ListNode* first = head;
    while (second) {
        ListNode *f = first->next, *s = second->next;
        first->next = second; second->next = f;
        first = f; second = s;
    }
}
```

Watch the seams: `slow->next = nullptr` terminates the first half (no accidental cycle), and the weave saves *both* next-pointers (`f`, `s`) before rewiring — the same save-before-clobber discipline as the reversal loop.

**Complexity:** $O(n)$ time, $O(1)$ space.

**What generalizes:** hard list problems are usually 2–3 easy primitives glued together — *recognizing the decomposition is the skill*. The same middle+reverse combo drives Palindrome Linked List; the weave reappears in merge problems.

**Why naive fails.** A hash map `original → clone` plus a second pass to wire `random` pointers is clean — but costs $O(n)$ extra space for the map. The interviewer wants $O(1)$ extra (not counting the output itself).

> [!INTUITION]
> The hash map only exists to answer one question: *given an original node, where is its clone?* If you park every clone **immediately after** its original, the list's own structure answers it: the clone is just `original->next`. The map becomes a pointer hop.

**The three passes:**

1. **Interleave:** insert each clone right after its original — `A → A' → B → B' → C → C'`.
2. **Wire randoms in place:** for each original `cur`, set `cur->next->random = cur->random->next`. Read it slowly: `cur->next` is *the clone*; `cur->random` is some original; `cur->random->next` is **that original's clone**. Pure pointer arithmetic, no map.
3. **Unweave:** detach the copy and restore the original list.

[[fig:m05-interleave-clone]]

```cpp
Node* copyRandomList(Node* head) {
    if (!head) return nullptr;
    for (Node* cur = head; cur; cur = cur->next->next) {   // 1. interleave clones
        Node* clone = new Node(cur->val);
        clone->next = cur->next;
        cur->next = clone;
    }
    for (Node* cur = head; cur; cur = cur->next->next)      // 2. set random via neighbours
        if (cur->random) cur->next->random = cur->random->next;
    Node dummy(0); Node* copyTail = &dummy;                 // 3. detach the copy
    for (Node* cur = head; cur; cur = cur->next) {
        copyTail->next = cur->next;
        copyTail = copyTail->next;
        cur->next = cur->next->next;                        // restore original
    }
    return dummy.next;
}
```

Note the loop steps: passes 1 and 2 hop **two** nodes (`cur->next->next`) to skip the clones; pass 3 hops one because it re-links as it goes. And do not skip step 3's restoration — leaving the original list mangled is an automatic follow-up question.

**Complexity:** $O(n)$ time, $O(1)$ extra space.

**What generalizes:** when you need a *node → partner* mapping, consider encoding it in the structure itself instead of a hash map. This *use the geometry as the map* idea also shows up in in-place array encodings (storing two values per slot).

**Why it is tricky.** Reversing one sublist is your memorized primitive — the pain is *reconnecting* the reversed block's two ends to the surrounding list, correctly, over and over. Off-by-one errors and lost tails are everywhere, and the very first block changes the head.

**The anchor scheme.** Keep a `groupPrev` pointer: the node just *before* the current block (initially the dummy).

1. From `groupPrev`, look ahead `k` nodes to confirm a full group exists — if not, stop and leave the tail as is.
2. Reverse the `k` nodes. The node that *was* first in the group becomes the **tail** of the reversed block.
3. Re-stitch: `groupPrev->next` → new block head (`kth`); then `groupPrev` advances to the old-first node for the next round.

> [!KEY]
> The elegant move: initialize `prev = groupNext` (the node *after* the group) instead of `nullptr`. Then the reversal loop links the block's tail straight into the rest of the list **as a side effect** — no separate re-linking step, no dangling tail, no accidental cycle.

```cpp
ListNode* reverseKGroup(ListNode* head, int k) {
    ListNode dummy(0); dummy.next = head;
    ListNode* groupPrev = &dummy;
    while (true) {
        // find the k-th node from groupPrev
        ListNode* kth = groupPrev;
        for (int i = 0; i < k && kth; i++) kth = kth->next;
        if (!kth) break;                         // fewer than k left -> done
        ListNode* groupNext = kth->next;         // first node AFTER the group
        // reverse the group, initializing prev to groupNext so the block
        // links straight into the rest of the list
        ListNode* prev = groupNext;
        ListNode* cur  = groupPrev->next;
        while (cur != groupNext) {
            ListNode* nxt = cur->next;
            cur->next = prev;
            prev = cur;
            cur = nxt;
        }
        ListNode* oldFirst = groupPrev->next;    // now the block's tail
        groupPrev->next = kth;                   // kth is the block's new head
        groupPrev = oldFirst;                     // advance anchor for next group
    }
    return dummy.next;
}
```

The dummy handles the first group changing the head; the `for` look-ahead handles the `<k` remainder; the `while (cur != groupNext)` bound reverses *exactly* `k` links.

**Complexity:** $O(n)$ time — each node is visited once by the look-ahead and once by the reversal — and $O(1)$ space.

**What generalizes:** the *anchor + look-ahead + primitive + re-stitch* frame works for any block-wise list transformation (swap pairs is just `k = 2`). Test it with `k` equal to the list length and `k = 1` — both seams must survive.
